\subsection{Hashing canonical JSON}

The canonical hash uses sorted JSON keys so that it depends on the meaning of
the question, not on the incidental order in which Python produced a mapping.

<<functions>>=
def question_hash(question: Question) -> str:
    """Return the full SHA-256 digest for ``question``."""

    payload = json.dumps(
        question.to_dict(),
        ensure_ascii=False,
        separators=(",", ":"),
        sort_keys=True,
    )
    return hashlib.sha256(payload.encode("utf-8")).hexdigest()
@

The hash is the stable identity of a question.  We therefore pin both the happy
path and a nearby change that must alter the digest.

<<test functions>>=
def test_question_hash_is_stable_for_identical_questions():
    first = MCQuestion("How was it?", ("Great", "OK", "Boring"))
    second = MCQuestion("How was it?", ("Great", "OK", "Boring"))

    digest = question_hash(first)

    assert digest == question_hash(second)
    assert re.fullmatch(r"[0-9a-f]{64}", digest)
@

Changing the option order changes the meaning of a poll, so it must also change
the canonical digest.

<<test functions>>=

def test_question_hash_changes_when_option_order_changes():
    first = MCQuestion("Pick one", ("A", "B", "C"))
    second = MCQuestion("Pick one", ("B", "A", "C"))

    assert question_hash(first) != question_hash(second)
